import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
import seaborn as sns

matplotlib.pyplot is a collection of command style functions that make Matplotlib work like MATLAB. Each Pyplot function makes some change to a figure. For example, a function creates a figure, a plotting area in a figure, plots some lines in a plotting area, decorates the plot with labels, etc.

Type of Plots we can plot in matplotlib¶

Bar      :   Make a bar plot
Barh     :   Make a horizontal bar plot
Boxplot  :   Make a box and whisker plot
Hist     :   Plot a Histogram 
hist2d   :   Make a 2d histogram plot
Pie      :   Plot a pie chart
Scatter  :   Make a scatter plot x vs y
Stackplot:   Draws a stacked area plot

Axis Functions¶

Axes     :   Add axes to the figure
Text     :   Add text to the axes
Title    :   Set a title of the current axes
Xlabel   :   Set the axis label of the current axis.
Xlim     :   Get or set the x limits of the current axes
xscale   :   Set the scaling of the axes
Xticks   :   Get or set the x-limits of the current tick locations and labels
Ylabel   :   Set the y axis label of the current axis
Ylim     :   Get or set the y-limits of the current axis
Yscale   :   Set the scaling of y-axis
Yticks   :   Get or set the y-limits of the current tick locations and labels

Figure Functions¶

Figtext  :   Add text to figure
Figure   :   Creates a new figure
Show     :   Display a figure
Savefig  :   Save the current figure
Close    :   Close the figure window

In [10]:
# Lets add the xlim and ylim to the above plot

m = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]

n = [30, 40, 45, 38, 48, 50, 37]

plt.plot(m, n, color = 'g', marker = '+', linewidth = 1.5, linestyle = 'dashdot')
plt.xlabel('Subjects')                  # adding labels to x axis
plt.ylabel('Scores')                    # adding labels to y axis
plt.title('Scorecard')                  # adding titles to entire graph

plt.xlim(left = 0, right = 8)           # setting the limit from 0 to 8 in x axis
plt.ylim(bottom = 20, top = 60)         # setting the limit from 20 to 60 in y axis
plt.show()
In [11]:
# Now I want the above graph to be bigger size

m = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]

n = [30, 40, 45, 38, 48, 50, 37]

plt.figure(figsize = (7, 5))             # adding the size to the below graph                                                         
plt.plot(m, n, color = 'g', marker = '+', linewidth = 1.5, linestyle = 'dashdot')
plt.xlabel('Subjects')
plt.ylabel('Scores')
plt.title('Scorecard')

plt.xlim(left = 0, right = 8)           # setting the limit from 0 to 8 in xaxis
plt.ylim(bottom = 20, top = 60)         # setting the limit from 20 to 60 in yaxis

plt.show()

Adding Lengend¶

In [34]:
x = [2, 5, 8 , 1 , 4 , 7, 3, 6, 9]

y1 = [24, 26, 35, 54, 68, 48, 59, ]

plt.plot(x, label = "X",color = 'g')
plt.plot(y, label = "Y", color = 'b')
plt.plot(y1, label = 'Y1', color = 'r')
plt.legend(loc = 2)
plt.show()

to change the location of legend to either top left plt.legend(loc = 2), (loc =1) for top right, bottom left (loc = 3)¶

What is grid?¶

It is a table like structure inside the graph

In [50]:
x = [2, 5, 8 , 1 , 4 , 7, 3, 6, 9]
y = [12, 32, 46, 15, 35, 48, 68, 75, 95]
y1 = [24, 26, 35, 54, 68, 48, 59, ]
plt.figure(figsize = (7,4))
plt.plot(x, label = "X",color = 'g')
plt.plot(y, label = "Y", color = 'b')
plt.plot(y1, label = 'Y1', color = 'r')
plt.legend(loc = 2)
plt.grid(True)   # we can also specify the color, linewidth as well
plt.show()

I want to specify the limit in x axis from (0 to 6 only) then we use : plt.xlim([0,6])¶

In [51]:
x = [2, 5, 8 , 1 , 4 , 7, 3, 6, 9]
y = [12, 32, 46, 15, 35, 48, 68, 75, 95]

plt.legend(loc = 2)
plt.grid(True)   # we can also specify the color, linewidth as well
plt.xlim([0,10]) # I have now specified the limit similiary ylim
plt.show()

In [56]:
# Step 2

data  = np.random.randn(2, 100)   # 2 arrays with each array 100 values from 0 to 1

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize = (9,7))   # (2,2) mean 2 rows plots and 2 column plots 

ax[0,0].hist(data[0])      # creating histogram

ax[1,0].scatter(data[0],data[1])   # creating scatter plot syntax: scatter(x, y)

ax[0,1].plot(data[0],data[1])    # normal plot syntax:  plot(x, y)

ax[1,1].hist2d(data[0],data[1])   # hist2d plot syntax: hist2d(x, y)

plt.show()

fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize = (12,7))

ax[0,0].hist(x)     # histogram hist(x)
plt.setp(ax[0,0], xlabel = 'Hist for x')    # setting the xlabel for first plot

ax[1,0].hist(y)     # histogram hist(y)
plt.setp(ax[1,0], xlabel = 'Hist for y')    # setting the xlabel for second plot

ax[0,1].scatter(x, y)   # scatterplot  scatter(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[0,1], xlabel = 'Scatterplot')

ax[1,1].plot(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[1,1], xlabel = 'Normal plot')

plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,3, figsize = (15, 7))

ax[0,0].bar(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[0,0], xlabel = 'barplot')               

ax[0,1].scatter(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[0,1], xlabel = 'scatterplot')

ax[0,2].plot(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[0,2], xlabel = 'lineargraph')

ax[1,0].barh(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[1,0], xlabel = 'barchart horizontal')

ax[1,1].stackplot(x,y)
plt.setp(ax[1,1], xlabel = 'stackplot')

ax[1,2].hist2d(x, y)
plt.setp(ax[1,2], xlabel = 'histogram 2 dimensional')

plt.suptitle("Basic plots in subplots")
plt.show()
